1
00:00:05,749 --> 00:00:10,393
Hi there. I'm Hannah McLeod, and I'm a narrative designer at Crystal Dynamics,

2
00:00:10,393 --> 00:00:14,836
and one of the writers on Marvel's Avengers. This is Getting the Most out of an Entry-Level

3
00:00:14,836 --> 00:00:18,759
Games job, and I thought the most appropriate way to get started would be to talk a little

4
00:00:18,759 --> 00:00:25,965
bit about my first job in the games industry. My first job was at Telltale Games, working on

5
00:00:25,965 --> 00:00:31,029
The Walking Dead A New Frontier, aka Season 3, and Minecraft Story Mode Season 2.

6
00:00:31,867 --> 00:00:38,911
My job title was Creative Development Assistant, or CDA for short. And if you have no idea what

7
00:00:38,911 --> 00:00:44,274
that title means, you're not alone. Most people at Telltale didn't know either.

8
00:00:44,274 --> 00:00:50,017
There were four of us. One CDA per project. And our primary duties involved taking court

9
00:00:50,017 --> 00:00:56,981
reporter-style notes in meetings and exporting voiceover scripts for recording sessions.

10
00:00:56,981 --> 00:01:00,783
I loved my job. But the reality of it could be a little jarring.

11
00:01:02,050 --> 00:01:03,591
We didn't have a manager.

12
00:01:03,591 --> 00:01:07,612
Well, we had a manager the first couple months at my job,

13
00:01:07,612 --> 00:01:10,113
and then she got promoted and moved apartments,

14
00:01:10,113 --> 00:01:12,654
and they never replaced her.

15
00:01:12,654 --> 00:01:14,374
We didn't have a promotion ladder.

16
00:01:14,374 --> 00:01:18,536
We had two CDAs, former CDAs, who'd

17
00:01:18,536 --> 00:01:22,697
moved into narrative design and audio design, respectively,

18
00:01:22,697 --> 00:01:24,718
but no clear idea how they did it

19
00:01:24,718 --> 00:01:26,598
and if that method would even work for us.

20
00:01:28,136 --> 00:01:31,157
We didn't even really have a department.

21
00:01:31,157 --> 00:01:34,398
We, well, our time card said we were in production,

22
00:01:34,398 --> 00:01:37,900
but we could answer to creative, audio,

23
00:01:37,900 --> 00:01:41,341
and it could change by the day, by the hour.

24
00:01:41,341 --> 00:01:43,442
We didn't really have a lot of training.

25
00:01:43,442 --> 00:01:46,663
Our training involved shadowing a CDA for a couple of weeks

26
00:01:46,663 --> 00:01:48,624
before getting dropped in the deep end

27
00:01:48,624 --> 00:01:50,004
of our own solo project.

28
00:01:51,545 --> 00:01:56,616
Despite, or I guess because of all of this, by the end of my tenure at Telltale,

29
00:01:56,616 --> 00:02:00,726
I was accredited writer on the last three episodes of Minecraft Story Mode Season 2.

30
00:02:01,940 --> 00:02:04,161
That's me.

31
00:02:04,161 --> 00:02:08,683
And from talking to other developers, I've realized I'm not special.

32
00:02:08,683 --> 00:02:14,105
Entry level positions in the games industry are rare.

33
00:02:14,105 --> 00:02:18,167
Even mine was phased out before the studio closed in 2018.

34
00:02:18,167 --> 00:02:19,848
So you kind of have to take what you can get.

35
00:02:19,848 --> 00:02:23,350
And it's not always the exact job you want.

36
00:02:23,350 --> 00:02:25,170
Beggars can't be choosers.

37
00:02:25,170 --> 00:02:28,712
And I don't think I can change the entire industry with one talks.

38
00:02:28,712 --> 00:02:31,273
Especially their approach to entry level positions.

39
00:02:31,753 --> 00:02:37,435
But I decided I'm going to try to give you a toolbox of sorts to get through this chaotic,

40
00:02:37,435 --> 00:02:43,396
often nebulous time in your game development career. A couple of caveats before we start,

41
00:02:43,396 --> 00:02:49,317
though. The studio I worked at no longer exists, which is why I can be pretty explicit with my job

42
00:02:49,317 --> 00:02:55,399
duties and examples of the things that I did. Not everyone has that opportunity. And, well,

43
00:02:55,399 --> 00:03:00,560
we're in an NDA world. So, I don't begrudge anyone not sharing more details about their

44
00:03:00,560 --> 00:03:01,200
first job.

45
00:03:02,141 --> 00:03:07,446
I also work in narrative, so most of my examples are going to be narrative-based, but the advice

46
00:03:07,446 --> 00:03:11,229
is meant to be as department-agnostic as possible.

47
00:03:12,150 --> 00:03:16,331
I also know that a lot of people, including myself, are still working remotely and maybe

48
00:03:16,331 --> 00:03:18,452
working remotely permanently.

49
00:03:18,452 --> 00:03:24,793
So I try to make the advice work if you're in a remote position or if you're in the office.

50
00:03:24,793 --> 00:03:29,475
So your mileage may vary, but I'm hoping by the end of this talk that you'll have at least

51
00:03:29,475 --> 00:03:34,936
one thing you can try to get yourself noticed, which is the goal, by the way.

52
00:03:34,936 --> 00:03:36,396
It's to get noticed in your first job.

53
00:03:36,396 --> 00:03:39,457
You succeed in this industry by building connections.

54
00:03:40,077 --> 00:03:45,819
Games are beautifully collaborative and notoriously unreliable. And the reason I

55
00:03:45,819 --> 00:03:52,441
can even be here today is because people noticed me and helped me forward. Yes,

56
00:03:52,441 --> 00:03:56,843
you also need to hone your skills and work hard and make a great game.

57
00:03:56,843 --> 00:04:00,904
But I would be nowhere without all of the people that I did those things with.

58
00:04:01,637 --> 00:04:09,641
In fact, even if you only get noticed by one person in your first job, that's a success.

59
00:04:09,641 --> 00:04:17,686
Congratulations. You've started building your network. And one last caveat. Do not do all of

60
00:04:17,686 --> 00:04:25,570
the things that I suggest in this talk at once for one job. I try to. And I don't recommend it.

61
00:04:25,570 --> 00:04:28,892
And I'll get into that a little bit more at the end.

62
00:04:31,847 --> 00:04:38,772
So the first piece of advice that I ever received was from Steve McManus, who was a designer who sat

63
00:04:38,772 --> 00:04:45,157
next to me at the open office at Telltale. He doesn't remember this, but a couple of weeks

64
00:04:45,157 --> 00:04:50,821
into my first job, he leaned over and suggested that I take my headphones off sometimes.

65
00:04:50,821 --> 00:04:54,885
Now, if you've ever worked in an open office, you know headphones are kind of necessary to get

66
00:04:55,722 --> 00:05:01,305
any work done. But what he meant was, if I listen to the studio around me, I might learn

67
00:05:01,305 --> 00:05:07,468
some things. And he was completely right. So right that I kind of use listening as core

68
00:05:07,468 --> 00:05:13,771
to all the rest of my advice in this talk. It's kind of your secret... It's kind of your

69
00:05:13,771 --> 00:05:18,654
super secret weapon that you can always fall back on when you're feeling overwhelmed or

70
00:05:18,654 --> 00:05:21,576
you're not sure what you should be doing. So...

71
00:05:23,455 --> 00:05:30,597
remotely listening looks a little different. It could mean following a Slack channel,

72
00:05:30,597 --> 00:05:37,560
even if you're not 100% sure it applies to you, or listening to the chit chat before and after

73
00:05:37,560 --> 00:05:42,542
a Zoom meeting, not just the meeting itself. Or it could even mean following an email thread

74
00:05:42,542 --> 00:05:43,062
as someone

75
00:05:44,222 --> 00:05:49,386
some team bats a proposal back and forth. So it's probably better to say, if you're remote,

76
00:05:49,386 --> 00:05:56,832
to keep your headphones on sometimes. Okay. So you have your super secret weapon. It's harder

77
00:05:56,832 --> 00:06:02,757
to say than I thought. Now it's time to talk about who you want to get noticed by in your first job.

78
00:06:02,757 --> 00:06:06,480
We're going to start really, really easy. Your manager.

79
00:06:07,575 --> 00:06:13,318
I know, I know. I just said I didn't have one in my first job and that's true. But I have one now

80
00:06:13,318 --> 00:06:18,841
and she's great. Hi, Nicole. And if you are lucky enough to have a manager in your first job,

81
00:06:18,841 --> 00:06:24,443
you got to use it. So if you don't know what a manager does, it's their job to kind of keep

82
00:06:24,443 --> 00:06:29,185
track of how well you're doing in your job. They will give you performance reviews if your studio

83
00:06:29,185 --> 00:06:33,988
has formal ones. And they're kind of your gatekeeper to any promotions that you might get.

84
00:06:35,048 --> 00:06:39,171
It's also their job to kind of gather feedback from your other teammates to see how well

85
00:06:39,171 --> 00:06:42,773
they like working with you and if they have any ways you could improve.

86
00:06:42,773 --> 00:06:47,256
Which is great because it avoids the awkward situation of having to ask people directly

87
00:06:47,256 --> 00:06:48,456
for that kind of feedback.

88
00:06:48,456 --> 00:06:55,741
The reason that it is so easy to get noticed by your manager is because it's literally

89
00:06:55,741 --> 00:07:00,023
their job to notice you and advocate for you in the studio.

90
00:07:00,023 --> 00:07:02,204
Now, not all managers are created equal.

91
00:07:03,134 --> 00:07:07,018
Some are more invested than others, but you're only really going to get as much from your

92
00:07:07,018 --> 00:07:12,062
manager relationship as you put into it. So the first way to get noticed by your manager is to

93
00:07:12,062 --> 00:07:18,008
tell them your career goals right from the start. I was clear in my interview for the CDA job that

94
00:07:18,008 --> 00:07:22,972
I wanted to be a game writer. I submitted writing samples with my resume and it just so happened

95
00:07:22,972 --> 00:07:26,655
that my temporary manager was one of the people interviewing me. So

96
00:07:27,316 --> 00:07:31,079
She also spread the word about my career goals,

97
00:07:31,079 --> 00:07:33,440
so that when I started on my first solo project,

98
00:07:33,440 --> 00:07:35,041
which was Minecraft Story Mode Season 2,

99
00:07:35,041 --> 00:07:36,723
the team already knew going in

100
00:07:36,723 --> 00:07:38,884
that that was something I wanted to do.

101
00:07:39,983 --> 00:07:46,790
And I am a woman in game development. So I know there is this hesitancy to not come across too

102
00:07:46,790 --> 00:07:52,015
ambitious in our work. But I want to nip that in the bud right now. No one expects an entry-level

103
00:07:52,015 --> 00:07:59,302
employee wants to be in that role forever. So sharing your ambitions is one step closer to

104
00:07:59,302 --> 00:08:02,085
making them a reality. So be ambitious.

105
00:08:02,907 --> 00:08:07,770
The other way to get noticed by your manager is to schedule weekly one-on-ones.

106
00:08:07,770 --> 00:08:12,673
So your manager is also a game developer, which means they're super busy.

107
00:08:12,673 --> 00:08:17,496
And they're even more so if they have to manage more people than just you.

108
00:08:17,496 --> 00:08:20,477
So you want to try to stay on their radar as much as possible.

109
00:08:20,477 --> 00:08:28,002
These one-on-ones can be short check-ins or long vent sessions, depending on your relationship.

110
00:08:28,802 --> 00:08:37,726
But it's supposed to be for talking about how the job is going and if you're having any issues that you need feedback or advice on

111
00:08:37,726 --> 00:08:42,768
And any feedback they might have for you on how you could do better. If you're remote

112
00:08:42,768 --> 00:08:48,111
I really suggest that you check in with your manager more often than just once a week

113
00:08:48,111 --> 00:08:53,833
Right now I work from home. So my manager and I are kind of in constant contact over Slack that way we can

114
00:08:54,594 --> 00:08:58,877
raise any issues that we're having as quickly as possible and we don't have to wait until

115
00:08:58,877 --> 00:09:04,181
the next check-in. There's this kind of out of sight, out of mind mentality if you don't do that.

116
00:09:04,181 --> 00:09:09,566
It's also fine to skip these one-on-ones occasionally if you don't have anything

117
00:09:09,566 --> 00:09:14,590
to talk about that week, but I highly recommend you keep them on the calendar so that your manager

118
00:09:14,590 --> 00:09:19,253
can see the notification and go, oh yeah, that person is here and they're doing well.

119
00:09:20,352 --> 00:09:26,037
If you don't have a manager or your manager isn't as invested as you'd like them to be,

120
00:09:26,037 --> 00:09:30,140
the next easiest person to get the attention of is the person you report to.

121
00:09:30,140 --> 00:09:34,984
So sometimes that is your manager, but for a lot of people, it's a different person.

122
00:09:34,984 --> 00:09:40,949
In fact, I gave a survey to some of my fellow game writers and I asked them what they wish

123
00:09:40,949 --> 00:09:43,992
they would have known before their first job in the industry.

124
00:09:43,992 --> 00:09:48,555
And a surprisingly large amount of people wish they'd known who they were supposed to

125
00:09:48,555 --> 00:09:48,996
report to.

126
00:09:50,441 --> 00:09:53,942
So some advice on figuring out who this person is.

127
00:09:53,942 --> 00:09:55,163
Ask during your interview.

128
00:09:55,163 --> 00:09:57,684
It's actually a really great question to ask early

129
00:09:57,684 --> 00:10:00,706
because it can give you an idea of what the position is for

130
00:10:00,706 --> 00:10:02,827
based on who it reports to.

131
00:10:02,827 --> 00:10:04,347
And if the person you report to

132
00:10:04,347 --> 00:10:05,908
happens to be in your interview,

133
00:10:05,908 --> 00:10:08,009
it gives you the chance to sort of

134
00:10:08,009 --> 00:10:09,870
ask about their leadership style

135
00:10:09,870 --> 00:10:11,491
and the day-to-day task load.

136
00:10:12,550 --> 00:10:17,996
If you miss the chance to ask during your interview, ask during orientation because

137
00:10:17,996 --> 00:10:23,382
the last thing you want is to be dropped off at your desk or dropped off of a Zoom call

138
00:10:23,382 --> 00:10:27,506
and not know who you're supposed to be talking to or what you're supposed to be doing.

139
00:10:28,568 --> 00:10:31,049
The person you receive your day-to-day tasks from

140
00:10:31,049 --> 00:10:32,089
is the person you report to.

141
00:10:32,089 --> 00:10:34,109
They're also the person that you show your work

142
00:10:34,109 --> 00:10:35,990
to to receive feedback.

143
00:10:35,990 --> 00:10:38,370
Also, this person can change.

144
00:10:38,370 --> 00:10:40,570
Unlike your manager, which tends to be pretty stable

145
00:10:40,570 --> 00:10:42,611
if you have one, the person you report to

146
00:10:42,611 --> 00:10:44,931
can change depending on the project you're on,

147
00:10:44,931 --> 00:10:48,152
what part of the production process you're in.

148
00:10:48,152 --> 00:10:50,652
For me, when I first started, the person I reported to

149
00:10:50,652 --> 00:10:52,953
was a fellow CDA who was training me.

150
00:10:52,953 --> 00:10:55,653
So I would report to him, and then he

151
00:10:55,653 --> 00:10:57,793
would divvy up his own tasks between us.

152
00:10:58,874 --> 00:11:02,536
When I got assigned to Minecraft Story Mode, it was still a pretty small team, so I answered

153
00:11:02,536 --> 00:11:07,018
directly to the lead writer, and he would have me do research and that sort of thing.

154
00:11:07,018 --> 00:11:11,240
As we got well into production, I answered to the creative producer, who was in charge

155
00:11:11,240 --> 00:11:14,362
of scheduling and meetings and all of that stuff.

156
00:11:14,362 --> 00:11:17,864
And then as we got to recording, because I was the one exporting the voiceover scripts,

157
00:11:17,864 --> 00:11:21,546
I would report to the voice director, and then would make sure that the VO was all getting

158
00:11:21,546 --> 00:11:24,568
in where it needed to be in the game.

159
00:11:28,798 --> 00:11:33,142
The way to get the person you report to to notice you.

160
00:11:33,142 --> 00:11:35,203
At first, it looks a lot like your manager.

161
00:11:35,203 --> 00:11:36,804
You want to tell them your career goals,

162
00:11:36,804 --> 00:11:38,285
but for a slightly different reason.

163
00:11:38,285 --> 00:11:40,747
The person you report to controls your tasks.

164
00:11:40,747 --> 00:11:42,389
So if they know your career goals,

165
00:11:42,389 --> 00:11:44,050
they can start tailoring those tasks

166
00:11:44,050 --> 00:11:46,071
to help you achieve those goals.

167
00:11:46,071 --> 00:11:49,554
They can also give you FaceTime with the departments

168
00:11:49,554 --> 00:11:51,675
you might want to join if you're not in the department

169
00:11:51,675 --> 00:11:52,876
that you want to be right now.

170
00:11:53,577 --> 00:11:58,918
And they can also volunteer you for tasks when you're too shy to, or maybe you aren't

171
00:11:58,918 --> 00:12:00,298
there when the task comes up.

172
00:12:00,298 --> 00:12:04,399
In fact, the person who reports you can end up being your biggest advocate for increased

173
00:12:04,399 --> 00:12:08,960
responsibilities and promotions because they see you every day.

174
00:12:08,960 --> 00:12:11,560
You can also schedule one-on-one meetings with them if you want.

175
00:12:11,560 --> 00:12:14,421
It's slightly less necessary because you're seeing them all the time.

176
00:12:14,421 --> 00:12:17,962
But if you feel like the person you report to could be doing more to help you with your

177
00:12:17,962 --> 00:12:20,082
career advancement, then absolutely set those up.

178
00:12:20,712 --> 00:12:25,614
But the best method to get the attention of the person you report to is actually to report

179
00:12:25,614 --> 00:12:26,314
to them.

180
00:12:26,314 --> 00:12:29,675
When you're out of tasks and not sure what you should be doing, go ask the person you

181
00:12:29,675 --> 00:12:31,916
report to if there's anything you can do to help.

182
00:12:31,916 --> 00:12:34,717
It shows initiative and that you can be depended on.

183
00:12:34,717 --> 00:12:38,258
And they might even give you tasks that they were thinking of doing themselves until they

184
00:12:38,258 --> 00:12:40,459
realized you were free.

185
00:12:40,459 --> 00:12:44,160
At Telltale, I really enjoyed the fact that I had multiple people to report to because

186
00:12:44,160 --> 00:12:49,162
it meant if one person didn't have any tasks for me, I could go to somebody else.

187
00:12:50,943 --> 00:12:56,246
The other way to get the attention of the person you report to is to employ our super

188
00:12:56,246 --> 00:12:59,048
secret weapon, listening.

189
00:12:59,048 --> 00:13:03,270
So when someone comes up to the person you report to and asks them for something, is

190
00:13:03,270 --> 00:13:06,412
it ever a task that you think you might be able to handle?

191
00:13:06,412 --> 00:13:09,174
Is there anything that's on their plate that you could take off their plate?

192
00:13:10,714 --> 00:13:16,876
For example, my creative producer was often asked for collated data of our voiceover process.

193
00:13:16,876 --> 00:13:23,058
So like, how many lines did we record for the last episode? What is the line count for this character?

194
00:13:23,058 --> 00:13:28,299
I knew that information was easy if slightly tedious to find, so I volunteered to do it.

195
00:13:28,299 --> 00:13:31,860
And then I put it together in a living document that I could update so that

196
00:13:31,860 --> 00:13:34,061
everyone who checked it had the most recent information.

197
00:13:35,080 --> 00:13:40,745
Our writers were often asked for Minecraft driven solutions to creative problems.

198
00:13:40,745 --> 00:13:46,429
So, it was a little hard for them to come like have an encyclopedic knowledge of Minecraft.

199
00:13:46,429 --> 00:13:50,312
So, I would volunteer to research things. Like if they needed a block that had certain

200
00:13:50,312 --> 00:13:57,158
characteristics, I would volunteer to research that for them. The upside of listening into what

201
00:13:57,158 --> 00:14:02,682
the person you report to is being asked to do is it means you don't have to be caught up on tasks.

202
00:14:02,682 --> 00:14:04,103
You are already up to speed.

203
00:14:05,371 --> 00:14:07,392
I get a lot of compliments for this even now.

204
00:14:07,392 --> 00:14:09,312
Basically, every time someone comes up

205
00:14:09,312 --> 00:14:10,373
to the person I report to,

206
00:14:10,373 --> 00:14:12,393
I would take one headphone off and listen in

207
00:14:12,393 --> 00:14:15,334
just in case an action came out of it and I could help.

208
00:14:15,334 --> 00:14:20,276
It also helps, the game of telephone that sometimes occurs

209
00:14:20,276 --> 00:14:22,617
when a task is getting to you can confuse

210
00:14:22,617 --> 00:14:24,358
like who asked for the task,

211
00:14:24,358 --> 00:14:26,418
what problem it was trying to solve,

212
00:14:26,418 --> 00:14:28,919
what exactly they want from you.

213
00:14:28,919 --> 00:14:31,280
So it's sometimes better to just hear it directly

214
00:14:31,280 --> 00:14:32,020
from the source.

215
00:14:33,167 --> 00:14:39,449
If you're not sitting near the person you report to, it's probably good to ask if you can be moved.

216
00:14:39,449 --> 00:14:43,931
If you can't or if you're remote, then you just need to be a little extra vigilant.

217
00:14:43,931 --> 00:14:49,713
So if you see that someone asks in an email for something from the person you report to,

218
00:14:49,713 --> 00:14:53,454
maybe it's worth following up on that. Or if they're tagged in Slack.

219
00:14:53,454 --> 00:14:57,396
Or my manager, who's also the person I report to right now,

220
00:14:57,776 --> 00:15:02,679
I have her JIRA tasks up on a board so that when someone sends something to her, I can see if it's

221
00:15:02,679 --> 00:15:07,663
something that I could take off her hands. The more of these kinds of tasks you complete,

