So for the rest of us,

447
00:29:49,907 --> 00:29:52,308
volunteering to playtest has a lot of different benefits.

448
00:29:52,308 --> 00:29:54,389
For example, it can get you in front of people

449
00:29:54,389 --> 00:29:55,489
you normally wouldn't talk to.

450
00:29:55,489 --> 00:29:58,030
For Minecraft Story Mode Season 2,

451
00:29:58,030 --> 00:30:00,431
we introduced a lot of new game mechanics.

452
00:30:00,431 --> 00:30:03,372
So I got to talk to programmers and things like that

453
00:30:03,372 --> 00:30:04,972
that I never would have normally spoken to

454
00:30:04,972 --> 00:30:06,533
just because I was testing their thing.

455
00:30:07,733 --> 00:30:10,195
I have very low skill level when it comes to playing games.

456
00:30:10,195 --> 00:30:11,296
I'm not very good.

457
00:30:11,296 --> 00:30:16,580
And that can sometimes be helpful for playtesting because I'm kind of the lowest common denominator

458
00:30:16,580 --> 00:30:16,720
player.

459
00:30:16,720 --> 00:30:22,545
Some review meetings will also ask that someone play the game while everyone else watches.

460
00:30:22,545 --> 00:30:28,649
I'm really nervous to do this because I don't have a lot of confidence in my skills.

461
00:30:28,649 --> 00:30:33,013
But at Telltale, that meant that the player was the one making the dialogue choices.

462
00:30:33,013 --> 00:30:34,354
So it was a little less scary.

463
00:30:36,235 --> 00:30:38,717
Just make sure to be ready to answer questions as you play.

464
00:30:38,717 --> 00:30:41,879
That's really the biggest point of playtesting.

465
00:30:41,879 --> 00:30:44,721
For example, I playtested a boss once for Avengers,

466
00:30:44,721 --> 00:30:48,965
and the designer asked me things like what visual cues I was picking up,

467
00:30:48,965 --> 00:30:52,947
or if I knew what I was supposed to be doing at any given moment.

468
00:30:53,628 --> 00:30:59,370
For Telltale, it was all about if you took a long time to make a choice or you chose the silent option.

469
00:30:59,370 --> 00:31:06,632
The question was, were there any choices that you felt were valid or did you think they were all valid?

470
00:31:06,632 --> 00:31:08,313
And that's why you didn't choose one.

471
00:31:08,313 --> 00:31:12,434
Our display text also was slightly different from the dialogue that would come after it.

472
00:31:12,434 --> 00:31:16,255
And so we were often asked if it felt like the game honored our choice.

473
00:31:16,917 --> 00:31:21,180
But really, you're just being a data point for whomever you're playdusting for.

474
00:31:21,180 --> 00:31:22,061
So just be honest.

475
00:31:22,061 --> 00:31:28,726
Next is Scratch VO, which is probably my favorite way to get to know my coworkers and to get

476
00:31:28,726 --> 00:31:32,569
attention from other members of the team.

477
00:31:33,190 --> 00:31:38,053
For people who don't know, Scratch is the temporary voiceover that's put into the game

478
00:31:38,053 --> 00:31:42,415
to help get levels on their feet before the script is really settled and before you bring

479
00:31:42,415 --> 00:31:45,197
in voice actors, which costs a lot of money.

480
00:31:45,197 --> 00:31:49,239
So this is typically done by employees who are decent at reading a line.

481
00:31:49,239 --> 00:31:51,040
They don't have to be super great actors.

482
00:31:51,040 --> 00:31:52,461
They just have to be nice to listen to.

483
00:31:53,682 --> 00:31:59,068
I did theater, in case you couldn't tell. I did theater growing up, so I really love doing Scratch.

484
00:31:59,068 --> 00:32:04,255
And I'm a woman in game development, and because there are so few of us, you tend to get asked to

485
00:32:04,255 --> 00:32:07,519
do practically every female character in the game, so it's really fun.

486
00:32:08,600 --> 00:32:10,940
I know not everybody is comfortable doing this.

487
00:32:10,940 --> 00:32:14,021
They don't like to do something that's silly

488
00:32:14,021 --> 00:32:15,381
or they feel silly

489
00:32:15,381 --> 00:32:17,421
or they don't like the sound of their own voice

490
00:32:17,421 --> 00:32:18,582
and that's okay.

491
00:32:18,582 --> 00:32:20,182
But I have been pleasantly surprised

492
00:32:20,182 --> 00:32:22,342
by every single one of my coworkers

493
00:32:22,342 --> 00:32:25,223
that's done Scratch Feo, seriously.

494
00:32:25,223 --> 00:32:27,363
Telltale even had employee table reads

495
00:32:27,363 --> 00:32:30,184
where employees would get assigned the roles

496
00:32:30,184 --> 00:32:32,344
and it kind of felt like you were in high school again

497
00:32:32,344 --> 00:32:33,524
reading a Shakespeare play,

498
00:32:33,524 --> 00:32:35,985
like there was that much giggling.

499
00:32:35,985 --> 00:32:37,865
But it was really like a team bonding.

500
00:32:38,226 --> 00:32:47,789
experience to do it. So why am I telling you to do ScratchVO? Number one, the audio team is the best.

501
00:32:48,467 --> 00:32:51,448
I am extremely biased because I work with them a lot,

502
00:32:51,448 --> 00:32:54,069
but the audio team, they're amazing.

503
00:32:54,069 --> 00:32:56,090
They're at the end of the pipeline,

504
00:32:56,090 --> 00:32:59,571
so they're often forgotten or left out of decision-making,

505
00:32:59,571 --> 00:33:02,453
even though they touch every single part of the game,

506
00:33:02,453 --> 00:33:04,253
like every single part.

507
00:33:04,253 --> 00:33:06,454
Like if you were an enemy designer

508
00:33:06,454 --> 00:33:08,475
and you're creating a robot army,

509
00:33:08,475 --> 00:33:11,076
don't you think that robot army would be so much scarier

510
00:33:11,076 --> 00:33:12,377
if they all spoke in unison

511
00:33:12,377 --> 00:33:15,318
and there was like this creepy radio fuss over their voice?

512
00:33:16,278 --> 00:33:20,299
or maybe you're a level designer and people are not figuring out that they need to go in the

513
00:33:20,299 --> 00:33:25,100
direction of the explosion because they keep missing the explosion. So, you add explosive

514
00:33:25,100 --> 00:33:29,261
noises, like, right in their ears so that they know they should be looking for one.

515
00:33:29,261 --> 00:33:37,783
They touch everything. So, getting some time with the audio team one-on-one doing ScratchVO just is

516
00:33:37,783 --> 00:33:41,704
going to make you a better collaborator. It means you're less likely to forget them when you're

517
00:33:41,704 --> 00:33:42,584
putting something together.

518
00:33:45,707 --> 00:33:48,808
It also lets you see the game's story from a different perspective.

519
00:33:48,808 --> 00:33:54,551
Let's say you don't touch the story practically at all in your day-to-day job,

520
00:33:54,551 --> 00:34:01,254
and you get asked to read for a minor villain, and you find out from their script that they're

521
00:34:01,254 --> 00:34:05,636
trying to take over the operation from the main villain. It's something you never would

522
00:34:05,636 --> 00:34:07,817
have known had you not come in and read that part.

523
00:34:09,085 --> 00:34:11,726
It also gives you a chance to get away from your desk.

524
00:34:11,726 --> 00:34:14,348
If you're remote, obviously you're still at your desk,

525
00:34:14,348 --> 00:34:18,870
but it's a nice break from whatever your job is.

526
00:34:18,870 --> 00:34:24,173
And probably my favorite part is you get noticed

527
00:34:24,173 --> 00:34:25,474
when your voice shows up in the game.

528
00:34:25,934 --> 00:34:33,196
Probably my favorite thing in the entire world is when I'm in a meeting and I'm talking and someone realizes why they've heard my voice before,

529
00:34:33,196 --> 00:34:37,397
especially if it's for a role that's very different from my own personality.

530
00:34:37,397 --> 00:34:42,118
Like I would be the Scratch voice for Stella, who was the minor villain in Minecraft Story Mode,

531
00:34:42,118 --> 00:34:45,159
and someone would go, oh my god, that was you!

532
00:34:45,159 --> 00:34:48,859
And immediate attention. It's really fun.

533
00:34:48,859 --> 00:34:55,381
Audio is always looking for more people to do Scratch, and I think a lot of the time it's because people don't know what it is or don't know that we do it.

534
00:34:56,142 --> 00:35:02,994
So please volunteer, even if it's just to read three lines from a character that immediately dies.

535
00:35:02,994 --> 00:35:08,103
It's a blast and you can get to know your audio team and it's awesome.

536
00:35:08,103 --> 00:35:08,263
Okay.

537
00:35:09,487 --> 00:35:14,111
One last way to get to know your coworkers and get noticed by them is to audit new hire training.

538
00:35:14,111 --> 00:35:20,056
Like I said at the beginning, onboarding and training in the industry is not universal,

539
00:35:20,056 --> 00:35:25,621
but if there's a formal process at your studio or you just know someone got hired in the position

540
00:35:25,621 --> 00:35:30,526
you want to be in or the position right above you, ask if you can listen in on their training.

541
00:35:30,526 --> 00:35:32,107
The worst they can say is say no.

542
00:35:32,748 --> 00:35:35,750
The worst they can do is say no.

543
00:35:35,750 --> 00:35:38,171
But it'll let you get to know people

544
00:35:38,171 --> 00:35:40,713
who are closer to your level.

545
00:35:40,713 --> 00:35:43,695
If it's someone who has the job just ahead of yours,

546
00:35:43,695 --> 00:35:45,616
they have been in your position recently.

547
00:35:45,616 --> 00:35:47,157
And you are basically peers.

548
00:35:47,157 --> 00:35:50,159
So you're going to be growing up in the studio together.

549
00:35:50,159 --> 00:35:52,381
So it's good to get to know them.

550
00:35:52,381 --> 00:35:54,142
It also lets you learn the kind of skills

551
00:35:54,142 --> 00:35:56,563
you'll need for your next promotion.

552
00:35:56,563 --> 00:35:59,505
And you can direct your self-study and all

553
00:35:59,505 --> 00:36:01,166
of that research toward bettering

554
00:36:01,166 --> 00:36:02,507
those particular skills.

555
00:36:03,730 --> 00:36:05,594
You also won't need as much onboarding.

556
00:36:05,594 --> 00:36:08,120
When you're promoted, you can hit the ground running

557
00:36:08,120 --> 00:36:09,723
because you've already had this training.

558
00:36:11,027 --> 00:36:15,628
It's valuable to listen in on this stuff, even if you think you know everything there is to know

559
00:36:15,628 --> 00:36:20,370
about that position, because hearing about it from somebody else will give you tips and tricks

560
00:36:20,370 --> 00:36:26,372
you never would have come up with on your own. At Telltale, we hired a big group of narrative

561
00:36:26,372 --> 00:36:30,733
designers and writers at the same time. And so our narrative design director put

562
00:36:30,733 --> 00:36:35,255
together a kind of formal class to teach them the

563
00:36:35,955 --> 00:36:43,282
proprietary engine and how we approach storytelling at the studio. And I asked to sit in. And I didn't

564
00:36:43,282 --> 00:36:46,825
participate because obviously this is their training. They're trying to get to the point

565
00:36:46,825 --> 00:36:51,208
where they can just jump in and work. So I didn't want to take time away from that. But it let me

566
00:36:51,208 --> 00:36:55,252
see more about the engine, which meant when I was actually writing for the game,

567
00:36:55,252 --> 00:36:57,334
I already knew all of the stuff I needed to.

568
00:36:58,134 --> 00:37:03,977
And I also got to know a lot of people who were new to the studio and were similar or just above me in level.

569
00:37:03,977 --> 00:37:08,219
And so it was a really great experience to kind of create a peer group.

570
00:37:08,219 --> 00:37:14,722
Plus, I was volunteering for a course taught by the narrative design director who had an opinion

571
00:37:14,722 --> 00:37:19,165
on whether or not I could be a narrative designer. So it was a good idea to get

572
00:37:19,165 --> 00:37:23,006
FaceTime with him too and show that kind of initiative. All right. So.

573
00:37:25,138 --> 00:37:26,559
work over, busy stuff over.

574
00:37:26,559 --> 00:37:30,580
It's time to talk about the best people

575
00:37:30,580 --> 00:37:33,281
to get noticed by at your studio.

576
00:37:33,281 --> 00:37:36,502
Friends.

577
00:37:36,502 --> 00:37:37,843
You are probably spending a lot of time

578
00:37:37,843 --> 00:37:40,764
at your studio at this point, or at the very least,

579
00:37:40,764 --> 00:37:43,925
on the computer with your studio at this point.

580
00:37:43,925 --> 00:37:46,686
And maybe you like the people you work with.

581
00:37:46,686 --> 00:37:48,807
Maybe you even want to be friends with them.

582
00:37:48,807 --> 00:37:51,548
I'm not going to teach you how to make friends and influence

583
00:37:51,548 --> 00:37:51,808
people.

584
00:37:52,148 --> 00:37:56,559
But I do have some unconventional methods for if you're still eating lunch alone, and

585
00:37:56,559 --> 00:38:00,849
you're just really nervous about talking to this really cool people who make games for

586
00:38:00,849 --> 00:38:01,410
a living.

587
00:38:03,130 --> 00:38:06,491
In addition to making you more comfortable at your studio, which is great,

588
00:38:06,491 --> 00:38:11,574
there's actually some job reasons that you may want to make friends at your studio.

589
00:38:11,574 --> 00:38:18,497
In that same survey where I asked people what they wish they would have known before they started at their first job,

590
00:38:18,497 --> 00:38:24,420
I got a lot of responses like this, wishing they'd known some of the internal politics or office gossip.

591
00:38:24,760 --> 00:38:29,743
at the studio because they'd kind of stumbled into some awkward situations without knowing it

592
00:38:29,743 --> 00:38:35,167
and kind of put their foot in their mouth. A lot of people are too embarrassed to ask

593
00:38:35,167 --> 00:38:40,110
about this kind of stuff to their manager or the person they report to or their co-workers

594
00:38:40,110 --> 00:38:45,374
that they don't know very well, but friends will give you the unvarnished truth.

595
00:38:46,655 --> 00:38:50,616
I relied on my friends a lot at Telltale for dealing with executive leadership and directors

596
00:38:50,616 --> 00:38:57,259
because I would observe something or see something or listen to something and be like,

597
00:38:57,259 --> 00:39:01,862
I don't understand what's going on here and I'm really worried about getting in the middle of it.

598
00:39:01,862 --> 00:39:06,764
So I would ask my friends and they could kind of clarify. So it avoided any kind of

599
00:39:06,764 --> 00:39:08,204
embarrassing situations.

600
00:39:10,205 --> 00:39:14,770
Another good thing about making friends at your studio is that it sort of dismantles

601
00:39:14,770 --> 00:39:21,739
or demystifies, I suppose, the hierarchies in your studio. It's kind of hard to be intimidated

602
00:39:21,739 --> 00:39:26,324
by the senior programmer if you're also killing him once a week in One Night Werewolf.

603
00:39:27,645 --> 00:39:33,186
I really like seeing people in both their professional and casual settings.

604
00:39:33,186 --> 00:39:37,847
At Crystal, while we were still in the office, we had a running lunch game of Resistance,

605
00:39:37,847 --> 00:39:39,608
which is a deception game.

606
00:39:39,608 --> 00:39:44,529
And it was always really fun when someone came up to one of my friends and asked them

607
00:39:44,529 --> 00:39:49,490
a work question, because they would go from absolutely lying about not being a spy to

608
00:39:49,490 --> 00:39:51,971
answering professional work question.

609
00:39:51,971 --> 00:39:56,472
And then they would go back, and it was so cool to see those two different settings.

610
00:39:56,552 --> 00:40:01,353
I couldn't be intimidated by them anymore. I saw at the Switch. How do you make these friends?

611
00:40:01,353 --> 00:40:07,954
You listen. You listen for opportunities to make friends. A lot of game developers are also board

612
00:40:07,954 --> 00:40:15,176
game nerds. Maybe there's a weekly board game night at your studio. Ours was on Fridays at Telltale.

613
00:40:15,176 --> 00:40:19,117
Maybe there's a game during lunch, like our Resistance game.

614
00:40:19,577 --> 00:40:26,121
Or something I was really proud of at Telltale is I volunteered to play a campaign of pandemic legacy

615
00:40:26,121 --> 00:40:31,424
with three co-workers I'd never spoken to before. We were from completely different departments

616
00:40:31,424 --> 00:40:37,387
and we ended up becoming this extremely tight-knit group that I would never have known about had I

617
00:40:37,387 --> 00:40:38,848
not put myself out there.

618
00:40:39,789 --> 00:40:44,450
Board games are really great because there's a task to complete, so there's less likely

619
00:40:44,450 --> 00:40:48,392
to be awkward silences or a lot of personal questions.

620
00:40:48,392 --> 00:40:52,333
Even if you're joining a long-standing board game group, they're going to be so focused

621
00:40:52,333 --> 00:40:57,575
on teaching you the rules and whatever homebrewed home rules they have that you're not going

622
00:40:57,575 --> 00:41:00,456
to be the center of attention quite as much as you think you will.

623
00:41:00,456 --> 00:41:04,478
And by the fourth or fifth game with these groups, you're going to feel like one of them.

624
00:41:04,926 --> 00:41:07,928
There's also Dungeons & Dragons.

625
00:41:07,928 --> 00:41:12,651
I didn't play a lot of D&D before I joined the games industry, but I'm really glad that

626
00:41:12,651 --> 00:41:17,754
I had some knowledge of it because though Dungeons & Dragons is more complicated than

627
00:41:17,754 --> 00:41:21,637
your average board game, it gives you a longer amount of time to get to know a group.

628
00:41:23,695 --> 00:41:29,617
So it also gives you this sort of standing social engagement outside of work, especially when you're an entry-level employee.

629
00:41:29,617 --> 00:41:34,118
You can kind of go work, work, work, work, work and not focus on anything else.

630
00:41:34,118 --> 00:41:38,820
So it's nice to have dedicated like four or five hours that we're going to be playing this game.

631
00:41:38,820 --> 00:41:43,062
So listen for games and groups that are looking for new players.

632
00:41:44,902 --> 00:41:48,403
Maybe if you don't want the time commitment of a full campaign,

633
00:41:48,403 --> 00:41:51,664
someone is putting together a one-shot with pre-generated characters.

634
00:41:51,664 --> 00:41:55,805
In fact, if the character sheet is what intimidates you, which it was for me,

635
00:41:55,805 --> 00:42:00,806
you can ask your game master to help you make the character, even make it for you.

636
00:42:00,806 --> 00:42:06,288
And so you can kind of dive in without all of the complicated math and skills and things like that.

637
00:42:08,235 --> 00:42:11,097
We had a running D&D game during lunch at Crystal.

638
00:42:11,097 --> 00:42:13,399
So we only played for an hour once a week,

639
00:42:13,399 --> 00:42:16,182
but we got to know so many different people at that table.

640
00:42:16,182 --> 00:42:20,466
And it was kind of cool to see

641
00:42:20,466 --> 00:42:23,069
who became sort of the heroes of the story.

642
00:42:23,069 --> 00:42:24,990
And I really, really liked that.

643
00:42:24,990 --> 00:42:26,332
And then during COVID,

644
00:42:26,332 --> 00:42:29,174
I actually joined an online game with a coworker

645
00:42:29,174 --> 00:42:31,016
and it let me get to know some people

646
00:42:31,016 --> 00:42:32,097
from different studios.

647
00:42:32,237 --> 00:42:33,498
which was pretty cool.

648
00:42:33,498 --> 00:42:36,360
And we hope to meet in person one day

649
00:42:36,360 --> 00:42:38,722
to roll dice at a table.

650
00:42:38,722 --> 00:42:41,084
So I'm by no means an expert in D&D,

651
00:42:41,084 --> 00:42:43,826
but every time I play with coworkers, it has been a blast.

652
00:42:43,826 --> 00:42:45,687
So I definitely recommend it.

653
00:42:45,687 --> 00:42:49,370
And if you want some less nerdy hobbies, OK.

654
00:42:49,370 --> 00:42:52,953
There's always sports.

655
00:42:52,953 --> 00:42:55,795
Telltale had a push-up club where once a day,

656
00:42:55,795 --> 00:42:57,897
people would get together to do 100 push-ups, which

657
00:42:57,897 --> 00:42:59,838
was always very interesting to see out the window.

658
00:43:01,599 --> 00:43:07,484
Maybe there's a running group at lunch that you could join or an intramural studio team.

659
00:43:07,484 --> 00:43:14,049
So maybe your studio faces the other offices in your office park and volleyball or something.

660
00:43:14,049 --> 00:43:20,874
Again, if you're not looking for a huge time commitment, maybe try out a studio fitness class.

661
00:43:20,874 --> 00:43:26,698
I visited our yoga class once or twice at Telltale and it was a cool bonding moment

662
00:43:26,698 --> 00:43:27,339
with a lot of people.

663
00:43:28,099 --> 00:43:35,683
Again, time commitment issues, look for one-off events, like maybe your studio organizes a

664
00:43:35,683 --> 00:43:39,525
karaoke night or one of the teams is going to do an escape room.

665
00:43:39,525 --> 00:43:44,568
I highly recommend looking for activities for the same reason that I recommend board

666
00:43:44,568 --> 00:43:45,208
games.

667
00:43:45,208 --> 00:43:50,011
If you have a task to complete, there's fewer awkward silences and it can be less uncomfortable

668
00:43:50,011 --> 00:43:54,053
than say a mixer or that kind of thing.

669
00:43:54,053 --> 00:43:56,114
Time for coffee might be nice, but...

670
00:43:56,835 --> 00:44:02,536
It's kind of hard to get the conversation flowing, especially with people you don't know very well.

671
00:44:02,536 --> 00:44:08,758
If you are remote, obviously, this is all a lot harder. But you just got to be looking for those

